[This data is published under an Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0) license]
How The Post mapped unsolved murders
The Washington Post collected data on more than 52
column2: 000 criminal homicides over the past decade in 50 of the largest American cities.

column1: The data included the location of the killing
column2: whether an arrest was made and
column4: basic demographic information about each victim.

column1: Reporters received data in many formats
column3: and worked for months to clean and standardize it
column4: comparing homicide counts and aggregate closure rates with FBI data to ensure the records were as accurate as possible.

column2: departments provided only partial information about the homicides
column5: court records and medical examiner reports
column6: to fill in the gaps. The data is more specific than the federal homicide data gathered annually by the FBI from police agencies nationwide.

column2: identifying arrest rates by geography in each city
column3: sharing the analysis with the local police department prior to publication.

column2: The Post followed definitions used in the FBI’s Uniform Crime Reporting Program. In that program
column3: homicides include murder and non-negligent manslaughter but exclude suicides
column5: justifiable homicides and deaths caused by negligence.

column1: The Post considered a homicide to be closed by arrest when police reported that to be the case.
Cases were counted as closed without arrest if they were reported by police to be “exceptionally cleared.” Those are cases in which there is sufficient evidence but an arrest is not possible
All other cases were classified as having no arrest.
Mass shootings or terrorist attacks in the cities of Las Vegas
column5: were included on the maps but not factored into annual local arrest rates.

column1: The 50 police departments were selected based on the size of the city and their violent crime reported to the the FBI in 2012
column2: the middle of the survey period. Most departments provided a decade of data

column1: To explore the geography of homicide arrests
column2: The Post created grids of almost 2 million uniformly sized squares over the cities. A kernel density analysis was used to estimate the arrest rate for each square based on the homicides and arrests in its vicinity.

column1: Because the shading takes into account homicides inside of a square and nearby
column2: a square may contain no homicides but be shaded.

column1: The methodology is commonly used by police departments to visualize crime patterns. The algorithm was taken from the CrimeStat Spatial Statistics Program from the National Institute of Justice.
Areas shaded in orange are places where fewer than one-third of the homicides resulted in an arrest. The overall arrest average for these areas nationally was 14 percent.
Areas shaded in blue are where two-thirds or more of the homicides resulted in an arrest. The national arrest rate for these areas was 89 percent.
Maps may also include zones with high concentrations of killings
column2: outlined in orange or blue. Unsolved zones
column4: had more than eight killings and an arrest rate of less than 30 percent. Zones outlined in blue had more than eight killings and an arrest rate of greater than 70 percent.
